4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT PROHIBITING DISCRIMINATORY ACTION AGAINST A PERSON
5 PROVIDING ADOPTION OR FOSTER CARE SERVICES BASED ON THE PERSON'S RELIGIOUS BELIEF;
6 PROVIDING DEFINITIONS; PROVIDING REMEDIES; AND PROVIDING A STATUTE OF LIMITATIONS.”
7
8 WHEREAS, the State of Montana seeks to place a child in a safe, loving, and supportive home
9 whenever the state is required to place a child with an adoptive or foster family; and
10 WHEREAS, adoption and foster care agencies in Montana assist families with adoption and foster
11 parent placements of children; and
12 WHEREAS, the adoption agencies and foster care providers of this state represent diverse
13 organizations and groups, some of which are faith-based and some of which are nonfaith-based; and
14 WHEREAS, children in need of placement services benefit from having as many adoption agencies
15 and foster care providers as possible because the more agencies and providers that take part in placement
16 services, the greater the likelihood that a child will find a permanent placement; and
17 WHEREAS, the United States Supreme Court in Fulton v. City of Philadelphia, 141 S. Ct. 1868 (2021),
18 recognized the benefits of having more and not fewer adoption agencies and foster care providers, stating that
19 "[m]aximizing the number of foster families and minimizing liability are important goals, but the City fails to show
20 that granting [Catholic Social Services] an exception will put those goals at risk. If anything, including CSS in
21 the program seems likely to increase, not reduce, the number of available foster parents"; and
22 WHEREAS, children and families benefit greatly from the adoption and foster care services provided by
23 faith-based and nonfaith-based child placing agencies; and
24 WHEREAS, faith-based organizations and groups have a lengthy and distinguished history of providing
25 adoption and foster care services in Montana; and
26 WHEREAS, private child-placing agencies and individuals, including faith-based child-placing agencies
27 and individuals, have the right to free exercise of religion under both the state and federal constitutions, which,
28 under well-settled principles of constitutional law, includes the freedom to abstain from conduct that conflicts
