1 with an agency's sincerely held religious beliefs; and
2 WHEREAS, ensuring that faith-based child-placing agencies can continue to provide adoption and
3 foster care services will benefit the children and families who receive those services; and
4 WHEREAS, the United States Constitution allows all adoption and foster care providers to operate
5 according to their beliefs without fear of unjust government punishment; and
6 WHEREAS, in the unanimous decision in Fulton v. City of Philadelphia, the U.S. Supreme Court made
7 clear that state governments violate the requirements of religious neutrality when they undermine religious
8 beliefs or practices and that the "[g]overnment fails to act neutrally when it proceeds in a manner intolerant of
9 religious beliefs or restricts practices because of their religious nature"; and
10 WHEREAS, the U.S. Supreme Court in Espinoza v. Montana Dept. of Revenue, 140 S. Ct. 2246, 2276
11 (2020) (Gorsuch, J., concurring), stated that "[t]he Constitution forbids laws that prohibit the free exercise of
12 religion. That guarantee protects not just the right to be a religious person, holding beliefs inwardly and secretly;
13 it also protects the right to act on those beliefs outwardly and publicly [italics removed]"; and
14 WHEREAS, the Espinoza Court noted that the U.S. Supreme Court has "long recognized the
15 importance of protecting religious actions, not just religious status" and, quoting Cantwell v. Connecticut, 310
16 U.S. 296, 3030 (1940), state that "the First Amendment protects the 'freedom to act' as well as the 'freedom to
17 believe'"; and
18 WHEREAS, in Thomas v. Review Bd. of Ind. Employment Security Div., 450 U.S. 707, 717-718 (1981),
19 the U.S. Supreme Court held that the government violates the Free Exercise Clause whenever it "conditions
20 receipt of an important benefit upon conduct prescribed by a religious faith, or... denies such a benefit because
21 of conduct mandated by a religious belief, thereby putting substantial pressure on an adherent to modify his
22 behavior and to violate his beliefs."
23
24 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
