2 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Discriminatory acts prohibited in adoption or foster care services.
3 (1) The state government may not take a discriminatory action against a person that advertises, provides, or
4 facilitates adoption or foster care services wholly or partially on the basis that the person:
5 (a) has provided or declines to provide an adoption or foster care service or related service based
6 on or in a manner consistent with the person's sincerely held religious belief; or
7 (b) maintains policies and procedures in accordance with the person's sincerely held religious
8 belief.
9 (2) (a) Except as provided, in subsection (2)(b), the state government may not take a
10 discriminatory action against a person whom the state grants custody of a foster or adoptive child or who seeks
11 from the state the custody of a foster or adoptive child wholly or partially on the basis that the person guides,
12 instructs, or raises a child or intends to guide, instruct, or raise a child based on or in a manner consistent with
13 the person's sincerely held religious belief.
14 (b) The state government may consider whether a person shares the same religion or faith
15 tradition as a foster or adoptive child when considering placement of the child in order to prioritize placement
16 with a person of the same religion or faith tradition.
17
18 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Remedies -- statute of limitations. (1) A person may assert a violation
19 of [section 2] as a claim against the state government in a judicial or administrative proceeding or as a defense
20 in a judicial or administrative proceeding without regard to whether the proceeding is brought by or in the name
21 of the state government, a private person, or another party.
22 (2) An action alleging a violation of [section 2]:
23 (a) must be brought no later than 2 years after the date the person knew or should have known
24 that a discriminatory action was taken against the person; and
25 (b) may be commenced, and relief may be granted, without regard to whether the person bringing
26 the action has sought or exhausted available administrative remedies.
27 (3) A person who successfully asserts a claim or defense for a violation of [section 2] may recover:
28 (a) declaratory or injunctive relief;
